<DOC><DOCNO> AP880908-0254 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 0213EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   09-08 0558</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0585</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Securities and Exchange Commission has filedcivil insider trading, fraud and stock manipulation charges againstthe investment firm Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., Michael Milken,the head of its junk bond trading unit, and others.   In the 184-page civil complaint, filed Wednesday at U.S.District Court in New York, the SEC said it would seek to have thedefendants surrender profits made on the affected stock trades andpay a penalty of three times the profits. The firm and Milkenreiterated previous statements denying any wrongdoing.   The suit capped months of speculation that the government hadassembled an extensive case against the firm as a result of theinvestigation into Wall Street abuses spawned by the Ivan Boeskyinsider trading scandal.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A former Morgan Stanley andamp; Co. rookie analyst,Stephen Sui-Kuan Wang Jr., 24, has pleaded guilty to the firstcriminal charges stemming from what the government has called thesecond-largest insider trading case in Wall Street history.   In another insider trading development on Wednesday, a firedMerrill Lynch andamp; Co. stockbroker, William Dillon, 34, pleaded guiltyto fraud after admitting he traded securities based on advanceknowledge of the contents of a stock-touting column inundistributed copies of Business Week magazine.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The nation's commercial banks enjoyed theirmost profitable six months on record through June this year,despite continuing losses in Texas, the government reports.   Commercial banks earned $10.5 billion in the first and secondquarters this year, topping the $9.7 billion in net income for thesecond and third quarters of 1985.   Also on Wednesday, a private panel of bankers, economists andlabor leaders released a report urging that banks and debtornations renegotiate existing loans rather than seek new ones tohelp ease the $1 trillion Third World debt problem.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Reagan administration has come up with apaperwork way to reduce the reported U.S. trade deficit by about $3billion before the election, but officials denied that theaccounting change was politically motivated.   Commerce Under Secretary Robert Ortner said Wednesday the changemade more sense economically.   The new procedures will change how merchandise imports getcounted each month.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Shareholders of Trans World Airlines Inc.overwhelmingly have approved Chairman Carl C. Icahn's proposal tobuy their shares and take the nation's seventh-largest airlineprivate.   But opposition to the move mounted Wednesday among TWA employeesas the 3,300-member pilots union sued Icahn in New York StateSupreme Court to block the privatization.   Airline industry analysts estimate the Icahn bid puts a value ofaround $40 a share, or $304.8 million, on the TWA shares that Icahndoesn't already own. TWA stock closed at $36.75 on the New YorkStock Exchange, up 37{ cents a share.</TEXT><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal judge has issued a restrainingorder temporarily blocking the $2.5 billion merger of Luckysupermarkets into American Stores, saying the combination threatensserious irreversible harm to Californians.   U.S. District Judge David Kenyon said Wednesday he would hold ahearing Sept. 16 on whether to grant a preliminary injunctionrequested by California Attorney General John Van de Kamp.   Van de Kamp wants a trial to decide whether the merger of thetwo supermarket giants is anti-competitive.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>